Incident.Summary: search warrant where a large amount of cannabis and U.S. currency was located

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
On 02/02/2023 at approximately 1055 hours, I, Sgt. J. Kellner, of the Easton Police Department, currently assigned to the Talbot County Drug Task Force, received a call from Lieutenant Hughes #0090, of Easton Police Department regarding a drug complaint at Quail Meadows apartments.

     Lt. Hughes advised patrol units were called to Quail Meadows located at 106 Meadow Drive, Apartment 103, Easton, Talbot County, MD, due to large amounts of controlled dangerous substances located in the residence.  I then made contact with PFC C. Westerfield, of the Easton Police Department, currently assigned to the Talbot County Drug Task Force, and requested him to respond to 106 Meadow Drive, Apartment 103, and meet with officer's on scene.

    PFC Westerfield responded and met with the regional property manager for TM Associates (which manages the Quail Meadows apartment complex), Stacy Todd.  Stacy Todd stated on 01/24/2023 all apartments had two notices attached to the door of each apartment.  One notice titled: "Notice of Intent to Enter" indicated management and/or an employee will enter each apartment on Monday, 2/6 and Tuesday, 2/7 for a fire inspection.  The second notice addressed to "Quail Meadows Residents", indicated a pre-inspection to take place at each apartment on Thursday, February 2, 2023 beginning at 10:00AM. This notice indicated the pre-inspection was to inspect maintenance items throughout the property.  Stacy Todd stated she knocked on the door to apartment 103 and did not receive a response.  She and another employee, Crystal Armentrout, entered apartment 103 to perform the inspection.  Upon entering the bedroom closet, which contained the hot water heater; an item to be inspected, she noticed several bags of suspected cannabis on the floor.  Next to the bags of suspected cannabis, were rubber bands and a currency counter.  Stacy Todd stated photographs were taken.  On a table next to the closet door, Stacy Todd observed the two notices that had been placed in the door on 1/24/2023.    Stacy Todd then exited and contacted police.  Stacy told PFC Westerfield the apartment was leased to Nevin Chester Jr. and he was the only name on the lease.

     PFC Westerfield is familiar with this apartment and Nevin Chester Jr., as he authored and executed a search and seizure warrant at this same apartment on February 9, 2022, where a large amount of CDS was seized from the bedroom closet of the residence, leased to Nevin Cordell Chester Jr., A/A/M, DOB: 3/17/1997.

    Officer's secured the apartment while I authored a search and seizure warrant for the residence of 106 Meadow Drive., Apt. 103, Easton, Talbot County, MD.  As I was preparing the search and seizure warrant, I was contacted by Sgt. G. Larrimore, of the Easton Police Department, who advised Nevin Chester Jr., arrived at the apartment around 1200 hours.  Sgt. Larrimore told Chester he could not enter his apartment, as officers were authoring a search and seizure warrant to enter the residence and seize contraband located by the property manager.  Chester told Sgt. Larrimore he possessed a "dispensary card", when questioned about having a "dispensary card" Chester Jr., stated he had "a card to smoke".  After speaking with Stacy Todd, Chester Jr., left the area in a red Chevrolet passenger vehicle, which officer's on scene conducted a registration check and the vehicle came back co-registered to Nevin Cordell Chester Jr., A/A/M, DOB: 3/17/1997.  I later viewed Sgt. Larrimore's body camera footage and confirmed this information.  This interaction was captured on Sgt. Larrimore's body camera.  I then sent a still image of the individual identified by Sgt. Larrimore and Stacy Todd, as Nevin Chester Jr., to PFC Westerfield, who also confirmed this individual to be Nevin Cordell Chester Jr., A/A/M, DOB: 3/17/1997. 

          
                 Nevin C. ChesterJr.
               B/M DOB: 03/17/1997
          106 Meadow Drive, Apt. 103
          Easton, Talbot County, MD 

     At 1419 hours, the search and seizure warrant was electronically submitted to Judge Joseph Riley, who was the Judge for the Talbot County District Court on 02/02/2023.  The Search and Seizure Warrant was ultimately signed at 1444 hours on 02/02/2023.

    The search and seizure warrant was executed by members of the Talbot County Drug Task Force and Easton Police Department at 1500 hours.  The apartment, which was unoccupied at the time of the execution of the search and seizure warrant was photographed, and a thorough search was conducted.  106 Meadow Drive, Apartment #103, is a second floor apartment.  The front door leads to a staircase which leads to the second floor of the apartment.  At the top of the staircase, you immediately enter the family room.  The family room leads to the kitchen.  From the family room, a hallway leads to a bathroom, as well as a bedroom.  There is a closet located in the bedroom.  This bedroom was identified as belonging to Nevin Cordell Chester, Jr., A/A/M, DOB: 3/17/1997.  A search of the bedroom of the apartment revealed several Ziploc and knotted bags of suspected cannabis located on the floor of the closet, next to the hot water heater. Also located was a currency counter, along with two bags of rubber bands.   Also located in the closet was a large cardboard box, containing multiple bags of suspected cannabis.  Some of the bags were labeled with various names, such as "Black Truffle" and "Runtz" among other names.  Located in the closet was a Sentry safe, which was opened by members of the task force.  Located in the safe were several bags of cannabis, index cards with the prices of various strains of cannabis, including the names listed above, broken down into the cost of various weights.  Also located in the safe was a large amount of U.S. currency in various denominations.

     Located on the desk, next to the closet door was the notice from the property manager, of the inspection to take place that day (2/2/23), with the pieces of suspected cannabis and ash on the notice.  Under the desk was a contraption that consisted of a make-shift air filter, presumably to absorb the odor emitted by large amounts of cannabis.  This box was made out of air filters on all four sides, with a box fan taped to the top.  The fan was facing outward, which would pull the air through the filters and out of the top of the box.

     Located on a window sill and on the tv stand in the bedroom were two digital scales.  Located on a shelf on the tv stand was an individual bag of suspected cannabis and rolling papers.  Located on a shelf on the tv stand were several spiral ring notebooks.  The top notebook was labeled "Numbers (The Books)", which contained names, such as, "Black Truffle" and "Frosted Runtz".  Next to the names were prices for various weights.  I know through my training knowledge and experience that these notebooks are drug ledgers, which contained names of various strains of cannabis and prices. 

   
 
     In the living room, a shoe box containing $272.00 in U.S. Currency, was located in the closet.  On a table in the living room were multiple pieces of mail in the name of Nevin C. Chester Jr.  Located next to the mail were prescription medication in the name of Nevin C. Chester Jr.  In the kitchen were multiple boxes of clear Ziploc and sandwich baggies.  

     Seized from the residence was the following items:
          Item #1 - 2 notebooks "vending machines" and "Numbers (The Books)"
          Item #2 - Multiple bags of suspected cannabis from closet floor
          Item #3 - Cardboard box containing multiple bags of suspected cannabis
          Item #4 - Bag of suspected cannabis from tv stand in bedroom
          Item #5 - 4 bags of suspected cannabis located in safe
          Item #6 - U.S. Currency located in shoe box 
          Items #7 - U.S. Currency located in safe 

     The U.S. currency was counted on scene and a Maryland State Police Receipt for Seized Property Form was filled out and left for Chester.  The area of the report for the MSP case # could not be completed, as the MSP barrack in Easton could not provide a case number due to technical difficulties.  The case number was emailed to me after the task force members had already cleared from the residence.  The amount of money written on the "detailed description of property" section of the form was $7812.00.  Due to the fact the residence was unoccupied, copies of the Receipt for Seized Property, Search Warrant inventory, and the Search Warrant Return were signed and left on the coffee table in the living room of the residence. 

     All items seized were transported to the Talbot County Drug Task Force office, where they were weighed and packaged according to policy and procedure.  Samples from the larger bags of suspected cannabis were packaged under PH#342759, and later taken to the MSP Barrack "I" property room, to be sent to the MSP Crime Lab for analysis.  The bulk of the suspected cannabis was packaged under PH#342758, and later taken to the MSP Barrack "I" property room for storage. The two notebooks were placed on a chain of custody only and taken to the MSP Barrack "I" property room for storage.  The following is the weight of each bag of suspected cannabis, seized from the residence and the amount of each sample to be sent to the MSP Crime Lab:

     The total weight of suspected cannabis seized was 6,927.9 grams.
     

     A preliminary count of the US Currency seized was conducted at the residence and believed to be $7,812.00 which was noted on the MSP Receipt for Seized Property, Search Warrant Inventory and Return and left at the residence for Nevin C. Chester Jr. Upon arriving back at the Talbot County Drug Task Force Office a secondary count of the US Currency seized was conducted and found to be $7,762.00. The mistake in counting took place as Currency was placed into stacks labeled with the amount of US Currency in each stack. One stack contained and was labeled "$1050.00" and another stack was found to contain "$950.00".  $50.00 in currency was taken out of the $1050.00 stack and placed in the $950.00 stack which was then labeled $1,000.  The "$950.00" was changed to indicate the stack now containing $1000.00, but the $50.00 was not changed on the stack labeled $1050.00.  Therefore, the currency count was off by $50.00. 
The money seized was in the following denominations:

 U.S. Currency Seized
     Twenty-two (22) - $1.00 U.S. Currency
     Six (6) - $5.00 U.S. Currency
     One (1) - $10.00 U.S. Currency
     Two-Hundred Eighty-Five (285) - $20.00 U.S. Currency 
     Twenty-Two (22) - $50.00 U.S. Currency
     Nine (9) - $100.00 in U.S. Currency
     Total - $7,762.00

     I know through my training, knowledge and experience that the amount of U.S. currency located, coupled with the denominations is a direct result of illegal drug proceeds.  The $7,762.00 was seized through the Talbot County Drug Task Force and held under CI#23-002, pending forfeiture.
     I know based on my training, knowledge, and experience that the items of evidence recovered are indicative of CDS possession, CDS paraphernalia, and CDS possession with the intent to distribute.  Furthermore, I know cannabis to be a Schedule I, Controlled Dangerous Substance.  I know based on my training, knowledge and experience, cannabis packaged in individual one ounce size bags, with the prices broken down by weight, and the fact that a ledger was located with the names of the various strains of cannabis located in the closet, is indicative of distribution of Controlled Dangerous Substances.  It is noted during the search of the residence, a currency counting machine and rubber bands were located next to the large amounts of suspected cannabis.  I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that distributors of Controlled Dangerous Substances often deal in large sums of currency.  Currency located in the residence was wrapped in rubber bands consistent with the ones found next to the currency counter. 
     
      Based on my training, knowledge and experience and insight gained through this investigation, I believe Nevin C. Chester Jr. possessed controlled dangerous substances in sufficient quantities to indicate the intent to distribute. 

     On 02/03/2023 at approximately 0839 hours, I electronically submitted the Search and Seizure Warrant Inventory and Return for the Honorable Judge Joseph H. Riley, Sitting Judge of the Talbot County District Court on 02/02/2023.    The return was signed on 02/03/2023 by The Honorable Judge Joseph H. Riley and returned to me on 02/07/2023 at 1547 hours.

     On 02/07/2023, an Application for Statement of Charges was completed on Nevin C. Chester, Jr. and taken to the Talbot County Commissioner's Office.  On 02/09/2023, an Arrest Warrant was issued for Nevin C. Chester, Jr., for the following:
          CDS: Possession with Intent to Distribute - Cannabis (CR 5-602 (b)
          CDS: Manufacture - Cannabis (CR 5-603)
          CDS: Possession - Cannabis Over Civil (CR 5-601 (a)(1)

     On 02/23/2023 at approximately 0023 hours, Nevin C. Chester Jr., turned himself in to the Easton Police Department.  Nevin C. Chester Jr., was taken to the Talbot County Department of Corrections, where he was seen by a Talbot County District Court Commissioner and held on no bond. Later that morning, a bail review was conducted and Nevin C. Chester Jr. was released on $10,000 unsecured bond.  
     
    I am a duly sworn Easton Police Officer and have been in law enforcement for 18 years.  During my career, I have received both formal and informal training concerning the identification, detection, packaging and trafficking of controlled dangerous substances.  I have arrested numerous suspects for violations of the Controlled Dangerous Substance laws of the State of Maryland and been successful in gaining convictions during subsequent prosecutions.  As a member of the Talbot County Drug Task Force I received training on a daily basis, as it relates to the street level drug crime trends.  During my career I have made numerous arrests related to drug crimes, and testified in Talbot County courts.  

     All events occurred in Talbot County, MD.  Case closed by arrest.
